notes.text:
An update for wireshark is now available for Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7.

Red Hat Product Security has rated this update as having a security impact of Moderate. A Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) base score, which gives a detailed severity rating, is available for each vulnerability from the CVE link(s) in the References section.
notes.title: Topic

notes.text:
The wireshark packages contain a network protocol analyzer used to capture and browse the traffic running on a computer network.

Security Fix(es):

* wireshark: Out-of-bounds read in packet-ldss.c (CVE-2018-11362)

* wireshark: Multiple dissectors could crash (wnpa-sec-2018-36) (CVE-2018-14340)

* wireshark: DICOM dissector infinite loop (wnpa-sec-2018-39) (CVE-2018-14341)

* wireshark: Bazaar dissector infinite loop (wnpa-sec-2018-40) (CVE-2018-14368)

* wireshark: SIGCOMP dissector crash in packet-sigcomp.c (CVE-2018-7418)

* wireshark: Radiotap dissector crash (CVE-2018-16057)

* wireshark: Infinite loop in the MMSE dissector (CVE-2018-19622)

For more details about the security issue(s), including the impact, a CVSS score, acknowledgments, and other related information, refer to the CVE page(s) listed in the References section.

Additional Changes:

For detailed information on changes in this release, see the Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7.8 Release Notes linked from the References section.

notes.text: A denial of service flaw was found in the SIGCOMP dissector in Wireshark. A remote network attacker could potentially use this flaw to crash Wireshark by tricking it into processing a crafted packet.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: wireshark: SIGCOMP dissector crash in packet-sigcomp.c
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text: The CVSS score(s) listed for this vulnerability do not reflect the associated product's status, and are included for informational purposes to better understand the severity of this vulnerability.
notes.title: CVSS score applicability

remediations.details:
For details on how to apply this update, which includes the changes described in this advisory, refer to:

https://access.redhat.com/articles/11258

All running instances of Wireshark must be restarted for the update to take effect.

vulnerabilities.title: wireshark: SIGCOMP dissector crash in packet-sigcomp.c

notes.text: A heap-based buffer overflow was found in the wireshark module responsible for analyzing the LDSS protocol. An attacker could create a malicious LDSS message to cause a remote denial of service, crashing the application.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

All running instances of Wireshark must be restarted for the update to take effect.

notes.text: In Wireshark 2.6.0 to 2.6.1, 2.4.0 to 2.4.7, and 2.2.0 to 2.2.15, dissectors that support zlib decompression could crash. This was addressed in epan/tvbuff_zlib.c by rejecting negative lengths to avoid a buffer over-read.

notes.text: In Wireshark 2.6.0 to 2.6.1, 2.4.0 to 2.4.7, and 2.2.0 to 2.2.15, the DICOM dissector could go into a large or infinite loop. This was addressed in epan/dissectors/packet-dcm.c by preventing an offset overflow.

cwe.name: Loop with Unreachable Exit Condition ('Infinite Loop')

notes.text: A vulnerability in MMSE dissector allows Wireshark to loop infinitely when parsing a specially crafted pcap file. Remote attacker could cause a denial of service to Wireshark by injecting malicious packets into the network that are automatically processed.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: wireshark: Infinite loop in the MMSE dissector
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text:
This issue affects the versions of wireshark as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5, 6, and 7.

Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5 is now in Extended Life Phase of the support and maintenance life cycle. This issue is not currently planned to be addressed in future updates. For additional information, refer to the Red Hat Enterprise Linux Life Cycle: https://access.redhat.com/support/policy/updates/errata/.

Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6 is now in Maintenance Support 2 Phase of the support and maintenance life cycle. This has been rated as having a security impact of Low, and is not currently planned to be addressed in future updates. For additional information, refer to the Red Hat Enterprise Linux Life Cycle: https://access.redhat.com/support/policy/updates/errata/.
